				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/natvoltaic" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2800867); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2800867&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610247985" alt="NatVoltaic" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2800867)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/natvoltaic" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2800867); return false;" >NatVoltaic</a></span> <span class="odate time_1598862073 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Aug 2020 08:21</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4763249">
									

<p>If there was any emotional resonance to be had it was lost under the all-too-cliche opening notes of importance, the piles of technobabble, and the sheer time it takes to reach the interesting parts (needing to destroy humanity to prevent universal destruction). The central concept is incredibly strong; as it stands, however, nothing is done to hasten the time it takes to focus on that or the human side of things.</p>
<p>Focus on technical detail can undeniably be cool but only if it evokes something other than &quot;this is how the thing works&quot; to the reader (such as generating the bizarre, disorienting horror of <a href="/scp-2717">SCP-2717</a>), or if it serves as a non-repetitive buildup to something substantial (such as the drama in <a href="/scp-5552">SCP-5552</a> or the science-grounded threat of <a href="/scp-2821">SCP-2821</a>). This achieves neither.</p>
<p>-1.</p>

