					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modulum" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3072585); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3072585&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610247985" alt="Modulum" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3072585)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modulum" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3072585); return false;" >Modulum</a></span> <span class="odate time_1598932898 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Sep 2020 04:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4764077">
									

<p>This is excellent. The idea of paradimensions is superbly clever and put to deeply scary and unnerving use here, and the way the scale of the story unfolds methodically with each new elaboration of the problem is Asimov-like in the way it examines all possibilities of the world and the laws created and then addresses them all. It helps the story sell the sheer multiversal/reality-level scale of the threat and adds to the hopeless tone throughout. I found it pretty easy to follow and it only increased the existential terror of the situation for me.</p>
<p>I will admit that the beginning document and ending note feel a bit clumsy to me and could be rewritten. It feels a bit explain-y and throwing in suicide doesn't feel earned; the best part of it were the final lines about the mutual purposes of the worlds.</p>
<p>- I'm not sure, but I would have loved to see what it would look like if you cut the O5 note and just end suddenly on the SCP-0000 description. It'd certainly make for the most brutal, crushing ending possible; I like the idea of that experiment, that lack of any closure. But I dunno if that's what you're going for.</p>

							</div>

								
					
