					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/squamous" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3484071); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3484071&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610247985" alt="Squamous" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3484071)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/squamous" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3484071); return false;" >Squamous</a></span> <span class="odate time_1599057768 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Sep 2020 14:42</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4765254">
									

<p>I really like this. I think it manages to avoid a lot of stumbling blocks that other world/reality ending SCPs suffer from: it's not overly long, it doesn't rely too much on confused concepts and there's no great big rambling blocks of nonsense that attempt to be deep or political. It's just a very clinically toned piece from one Foundation to another, with just enough feelsbait at the end. I like the idea of humanity and multiverse theory being the anomalies, that's just great. I feel like this does multiversal threat a lot better than Atonement or Project Palisade manage to.</p>
<p>This does make me glad for the no canon rule because the way alternate universes work isn't really compatible with a bunch of other SCPs, but the concept for differing universes in this entry is explained really well.</p>

							</div>

								
					
